                    ctmm
                    implements all of the
                    {CTSP}
                    s currently in use in the ecological literature and couples them with powerful statistical methods for autocorrelated data adapted from geostatistics and signal processing, including variograms, periodograms and non‐Markovian maximum likelihood estimation.
                  
                
                
                  
                    ctmm
                    is built around a standard workflow that begins with visual diagnostics, proceeds to candidate model identification, and then to maximum likelihood fitting and
                    {AIC}
                    ‐based model selection. Once an accurate
                    {CTSP}
                    for the data has been fitted and selected, analyses that require such a model, such as quantifying home range areas via autocorrelated kernel density estimation or estimating occurrence distributions via time‐series Kriging, can then be performed.
                  
                
                
                  
                    We use a case study with African buffalo to demonstrate the capabilities of
